The paper discusses an extension of compressed sensing that bridges the gap between theory and real-world applications. It introduces a mathematical framework that generalizes the three standard pillars of compressed sensing to three new concepts, which are likely to fall under the category of information theory (cs.IT). The paper also mentions several real-world applications such as medical imaging, microscopy, and spectroscopy, which are likely to fall under the categories of computer vision (cs.CV), multimedia (cs.MM), and signal processing (cs.SI). Additionally, the paper discusses the design of sensing mechanisms, which could fall under the category of numerical analysis (cs.NA).
